
Why Prefer MongoDB over SQL?
1. Flexible Schema
        json// Document 1
        { "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@mail.com" }
        // Document 2 — different fields, same collection. Totally fine!
        { "name": "Bob", "email": "bob@mail.com", "age": 25, "address": { "city": "NYC" } }
        SQL requires every row to have the **same columns**. 
        MongoDB lets each document have its own structure — great when your data evolves frequently.

 2. Horizontal Scaling (Sharding)
        SQL (Vertical Scaling)          MongoDB (Horizontal Scaling)
        ┌─────────────┐                 ┌────────┐ ┌────────┐ ┌────────┐
        │ Bigger &    │                 │ Shard1 │ │ Shard2 │ │ Shard3 │
        │ Bigger      │       vs        │ Node   │ │ Node   │ │ Node   │
        │ Server 💰   │                 └────────┘ └────────┘ └────────┘
        └─────────────┘                   Distribute data across cheap nodes
        MongoDB scales out (more servers), SQL typically scales up (bigger server) — MongoDB wins at massive scale.

3. Document Model = Natural Object Mapping
    java// In SQL — you'd need 3 tables: users, addresses, phones
    // In MongoDB — one document, mirrors your Java object perfectly
    @Document
    public class User {
        private String name;
        private Address address;          // embedded object
        private List<String> phoneNums;   // array — no join table needed!
    }
    No complex JOINs or ORM gymnastics. The document is your object.

4. High Write Throughput
    MongoDB is optimized for fast writes — ideal for:
        Real-time analytics
        IoT sensor data
        Activity/event logging
        Chat messages

5. Rich, Developer-Friendly Querying
    javascript// Nested queries, arrays, regex — all natively supported
    db.users.find({
      "address.city": "Mumbai",
      "tags": { $in: ["admin", "moderator"] },
      "age": { $gte: 18 }
    })

6. Built-in Replication
    MongoDB's Replica Sets give you automatic failover and high availability out of the box, with minimal config.
Feature        MongoDB                    SQL (e.g. MySQL/Postgres)
Schema         Flexible / Dynamic         Fixed / Rigid
Scaling        Horizontal (sharding)      Vertical (mostly)
Relationships  Embedding / References     JOINs
Transactions   Supported (v4.0+)          Native & mature
Query Language MongoDB Query Language     SQL (standardized)
Speed (writes) Very fast                   Moderate
Data integrity App-level                    DB-level (constraints)
Best for        Unstructured/varied data   Relational, structured data

⚠️ Limitations of MongoDB:
1. No True JOIN Support
        javascript// MongoDB has $lookup, but it's clunky compared to SQL JOIN
        // And it's NOT optimized for deeply relational data
        db.orders.aggregate([
          { $lookup: {
              from: "users",
              localField: "userId",
              foreignField: "_id",
              as: "userDetails"
          }}
        ])
        If your data is highly relational (many foreign keys, many joins), SQL is far superior.

2. Transactions Are Limited
        Multi-document ACID transactions were only added in v4.0 (2018)
        They work, but are slower and more complex than SQL transactions
        SQL databases have had battle-tested transactions for decades

3. Data Duplication (Denormalization)
        json// You often embed data instead of referencing
        // If "city" changes, you may need to update THOUSANDS of documents
        { "name": "Alice", "city": "Mumbai" }
        { "name": "Bob",   "city": "Mumbai" }  // duplicated!
        { "name": "Carol", "city": "Mumbai" }  // duplicated!
        This leads to data inconsistency risks if not managed carefully.

4. No Enforced Schema = Risk
        MongoDB won't stop bad data from entering:
        json// All valid in MongoDB — nightmare for your application!
        { "age": 25 }
        { "age": "twenty-five" }
        { "age": null }
        { "AGE": 25 }
        You must enforce validation at the application level (or use MongoDB Schema Validation).

5. Memory Usage
        MongoDB keeps working data in RAM for performance. 
        Large datasets with many concurrent queries can be memory-hungry compared to SQL databases.

6. Aggregation Complexity
        Complex reporting and analytics (GROUP BY, HAVING, window functions) are much simpler in SQL:
        sql-- SQL: Clean and readable
        SELECT department, AVG(salary) FROM employees
        GROUP BY department HAVING AVG(salary) > 50000;
        javascript// MongoDB: Verbose pipeline
        db.employees.aggregate([
          { $group: { _id: "$department", avgSalary: { $avg: "$salary" } } },
          { $match: { avgSalary: { $gt: 50000 } } }
        ])

When to Use What
Use MongoDB when:                    Use SQL when:
✅ Schema changes frequently         ✅ Data is highly relational
✅ Massive scale / high writes       ✅ Financial/banking systems
✅ Hierarchical/nested data          ✅ Complex reporting & analytics
✅ Rapid prototyping                 ✅ Strong ACID compliance needed
✅ Real-time apps, IoT, logs         ✅ Data integrity is critical
✅ Content management systems        ✅ Legacy enterprise systems

Sharding:
Sharding is MongoDB's way of splitting data across multiple machines (called shards) to handle datasets too large for a single server.
WITHOUT Sharding                    WITH Sharding
┌─────────────────┐                ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐ ┌──────────┐
│   Single Server │                │  Shard 1 │ │  Shard 2 │ │  Shard 3 │
│                 │                │ Users    │ │ Users    │ │ Users    │
│  100M documents │      →         │ A–H      │ │  I–Q     │ │  R–Z     │
│  💥 Too slow!   │                │ 33M docs │ │ 33M docs │ │ 34M docs │
└─────────────────┘                └──────────┘ └──────────┘ └──────────┘
Sharding Architecture
                        ┌─────────────┐
     App / Client  ───► │   mongos    │  ← Query Router (entry point)
                        │  (Router)   │
                        └──────┬──────┘
                               │  reads config
                        ┌──────▼──────┐
                        │Config Server│  ← Stores shard metadata & chunk map
                        └──────┬──────┘
                               │ routes to correct shard
              ┌────────────────┼────────────────┐
              ▼                ▼                 ▼
        ┌──────────┐    ┌──────────┐      ┌──────────┐
        │ Shard 1  │    │ Shard 2  │      │ Shard 3  │
        │(Replica  │    │(Replica  │      │(Replica  │
        │  Set)    │    │  Set)    │      │  Set)    │
        └──────────┘    └──────────┘      └──────────┘
3 Core Components:
Component        Role
mongos           Query router — your app talks to this
Config Server    Stores chunk-to-shard mapping
Shards           Actual data storage (each is a replica set)

Shard Key — The Most Important Decision
        The shard key is the field MongoDB uses to decide which shard a document goes to.
                javascript// Enable sharding on database
                sh.enableSharding("mydb")
                // Shard a collection by "userId"
                sh.shardCollection("mydb.orders", { "userId": 1 })

Types of Sharding:
1. Range-Based Sharding    
        Shard Key: age
        ┌─────────────┬─────────────┬─────────────┐
        │   Shard 1   │   Shard 2   │   Shard 3   │
        │  age: 1–30  │  age: 31–60 │  age: 61–90 │
        └─────────────┴─────────────┴─────────────┘
        ✅ Good for range queries (age > 20 AND age < 40)
        ❌ Risk of hotspots if most users are in one range
 2. Hashed Sharding
        Shard Key: hash(userId)
        ┌──────────────┬──────────────┬──────────────┐
        │    Shard 1   │    Shard 2   │    Shard 3   │
        │ hash 0–333   │ hash 334–666 │ hash 667–999 │
        └──────────────┴──────────────┴──────────────┘
        ✅ Evenly distributes data — no hotspots
        ❌ Bad for range queries (data is scattered)
 3. Zone-Based Sharding
        // Route data by geography
        sh.addShardToZone("shard1", "ASIA")
        sh.addShardToZone("shard2", "US")
        // Mumbai users → Shard 1, NY users → Shard 2
        ✅ Great for compliance (data residency laws)
        ✅ Reduces latency for regional users
Good vs Bad Shard Keys
❌ BAD Shard Keys              ✅ GOOD Shard Keys
─────────────────────          ──────────────────────
_id (ObjectId — monotonic)     { userId: "hashed" }
timestamp (always increasing)  { country: 1, userId: 1 }  ← compound
status ("active"/"inactive")   { email: "hashed" }
low cardinality fields         high cardinality + random

A bad shard key causes a **hotspot** — all writes pile onto one shard, defeating the purpose.

### Chunks — How Data is Distributed

MongoDB splits shard data into **chunks** (default 128MB each):
Shard 1:  [A ──── D] [D ──── G]
Shard 2:  [G ──── M] [M ──── R]
Shard 3:  [R ──── Z]
// When a chunk gets too big → MongoDB splits & rebalances automatically

When to Use Sharding?
✅ Use Sharding when:               ❌ Don't Shard when:
Data > single server capacity       Data fits comfortably in one server
Write throughput is the bottleneck  Read-heavy workloads (use replicas)
Need geographic data distribution   You need complex multi-shard txns
Horizontal scale is required        App is still in early stage

BSON:
BSON = Binary JSON
it's the binary-encoded format MongoDB uses internally to store and transfer documents.
JSON  →  Human readable text
BSON  →  Binary representation of JSON (what MongoDB actually stores)

JSON vs BSON
JSON (what you write)              BSON (what MongoDB stores)
──────────────────────             ──────────────────────────
{                                  \x16\x00\x00\x00          ← doc size
  "name": "Alice",                 \x02 name\x00 \x06Alice\x00
  "age": 25                        \x10 age\x00 \x19\x00\x00\x00
}                                  \x00                      ← terminator

Plain text, ~28 bytes              Binary, faster to parse, type-aware

 Key Advantages:
 1. Rich Data Types Beyond JSON
JSON Types (only 6):        BSON Extra Types:
─────────────────           ──────────────────────────────
String                      ✅ Date         (not in JSON!)
Number                      ✅ ObjectId     (unique IDs)
Boolean                     ✅ Binary Data  (images, files)
Array                       ✅ Int32 / Int64 (typed integers)
Object                      ✅ Decimal128   (precise decimals)
Null                        ✅ Regex        (stored patterns)
                            ✅ Timestamp    (internal use)
                            ✅ JavaScript code

2. Faster to Parse:
JSON → must scan character by character to find field boundaries
BSON → stores field LENGTH upfront → jump directly to any field

JSON:  { "name": "Alice" }  → parse char by char
BSON:  [5]["name"][5]["Alice"] → skip directly to value ⚡

3. Traversable — Skip Fields Efficiently
BSON document: [totalSize][type+name+valueSize+value][type+name+valueSize+value]...
To skip "address" and get "age":
→ Read valueSize of "address" → jump over it → read "age" directly
→ No need to parse the entire document!

BSON ObjectId — The Default `_id`

Every MongoDB document gets an `_id` of type **ObjectId** by default:
ObjectId("507f1f77bcf86cd799439011")
          └────────────────────────┘
               24 hex characters = 12 bytes

Breaking it down:
┌──────────────┬──────────────┬──────────────┬──────────────┐
│  4 bytes     │  5 bytes     │  3 bytes     │              │
│  Unix        │  Random      │  Incrementing│              │
│  Timestamp   │  Value       │  Counter     │              │
│  (seconds)   │  (machine+   │              │              │
│              │   process)   │              │              │
└──────────────┴──────────────┴──────────────┴──────────────┘
This means ObjectId is:

Globally unique across machines
Sortable by creation time (first 4 bytes = timestamp)
Lightweight — only 12 bytes vs a UUID's 16 bytes

java// In Spring Boot
@Id
private String id;  // Spring auto-converts ObjectId ↔ String
// Or use ObjectId directly
@Id
private ObjectId id;

// Extract timestamp from ObjectId
ObjectId oid = new ObjectId("507f1f77bcf86cd799439011");
Date createdAt = oid.getDate();  // when the doc was created — for free!

BSON Data Types in Spring Boot / Java
java@Document(collection = "products")
public class Product {

    @Id
    private ObjectId id;              // BSON: ObjectId
    private String name;              // BSON: String
    private int quantity;             // BSON: Int32
    private long views;               // BSON: Int64
    private double price;             // BSON: Double
    private Decimal128 exactPrice;    // BSON: Decimal128 (financial precision!)
    private Date createdAt;           // BSON: Date
    private byte[] thumbnail;         // BSON: Binary
    private Pattern namePattern;      // BSON: Regex
    private List<String> tags;        // BSON: Array
}

